## Installation and Configuration Steps

### Step 1: Download PuTTY

Download the PuTTY SSH client from the official website.

https://www.putty.org

Install PuTTY on your Windows system.

---

### Step 2: Configure PuTTY

After installation, open PuTTY.

You will see the PuTTY configuration interface where you can specify the IP address of the remote Ubuntu server.

---

### Step 3: Configure Ubuntu Network Adapter

If Ubuntu is running inside VirtualBox, change the network adapter mode to:

Bridge Adapter

This allows the virtual machine to obtain an IP address from the same network as the host machine.

---

### Step 4: Find Ubuntu Server IP Address

Run the following command in the Ubuntu terminal:

ip addr

or

hostname -I

Example output:

192.168.1.105

This IP address will be used to connect through PuTTY.

---

### Step 5: Enable Remote Access (Install SSH)

Update the system:

sudo apt update

Install OpenSSH Server:

sudo apt install openssh-server

---

### Step 6: Start SSH Service

Start the SSH service:

sudo systemctl start ssh

Enable SSH service at boot:

sudo systemctl enable ssh

Verify the service status:

sudo systemctl status ssh

---

### Step 7: Configure PuTTY with Server IP

1. Open PuTTY
2. Enter the Ubuntu server IP address
3. Select connection type as SSH
4. Click Open

---

### Step 8: Access Ubuntu Server

A login terminal will appear.

Enter your Ubuntu username and password.

Example:

login as: ubuntu
password: ********

You will now have remote access to the Ubuntu server.

---

### Step 9: Verify Remote Connection

Once logged in successfully, you can run Linux commands remotely.

Example command:

whoami

This confirms that the remote SSH session is active.

